1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:10,000
From the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture.

2
00:00:10,000 --> 00:00:14,000
You're way, way, way for the guy.

3
00:00:14,000 --> 00:00:17,000
Hopefully, you're sitting out.

4
00:00:17,000 --> 00:00:18,000
Ready?

5
00:00:18,000 --> 00:00:21,000
Okay. Good morning.

6
00:00:21,000 --> 00:00:28,000
Good morning. Today is August 18, 2013, where in Brooklyn, New York with Dr. John Carlos.

7
00:00:28,000 --> 00:00:31,000
Very honored to be here talking to you today.

8
00:00:31,000 --> 00:00:46,000
My name is David Klein. I am from the Department of History at Virginia Tech University and conducting this interview for the Civil Rights History Project of the Smithsonian's National Museum of African American History and Culture and the Library of Congress.

9
00:00:46,000 --> 00:00:58,000
Filming this interview is Mr. John Bishop of Media Generation. We also have Elaine Nichols here from the museum and our friend Sonom is also joining us today.

10
00:00:58,000 --> 00:01:05,000
I think that's everything. I want to thank you very much Dr. Carlos for being part of this project.

11
00:01:05,000 --> 00:01:12,000
It's my honor. I mean, this is a very prestigious interview and I'm just honored to be a part of it.

12
00:01:12,000 --> 00:01:16,000
Well, we're very grateful and honored that you've agreed to join us.

13
00:01:16,000 --> 00:01:17,000
Thank you.

14
00:01:17,000 --> 00:01:24,000
Great. What I'd like to do is just start if you could tell us a little bit about your childhood, where you grew up and really who your people are.

15
00:01:24,000 --> 00:01:31,000
And what sort of influences you may have seen from that background in your later life?

16
00:01:31,000 --> 00:01:35,000
All right. Well, let me just start off by my mom and dad.

17
00:01:35,000 --> 00:01:45,000
My dad was born, I would say probably about 60 years after slavery in Camden, South Carolina.

18
00:01:45,000 --> 00:01:52,000
My mom was born in Cuba, migrated to the United States when she was 17.

19
00:01:52,000 --> 00:02:01,000
I met my dad in New York City. They got married. They had three kids.

20
00:02:01,000 --> 00:02:10,000
Earl, Junior, Andrew, Carlos. Well, actually four kids. I'm sorry, I left my baby sister.

21
00:02:10,000 --> 00:02:16,000
John Carlos and then Hepsy Carlos. We're born and raised on Linux Avenue, New York.

22
00:02:16,000 --> 00:02:33,000
Fortunately for me, I had the great distinction to be raised between the Cotton Club and the Savoy Barroom, probably the two most prestigious night clubs in the world at that particular time.

23
00:02:33,000 --> 00:02:45,000
I had an opportunity to grow up there to learn about how to hustle in front of the Savoy Barroom, to do a little song and dance, entertain the people and receive those silver dollars.

24
00:02:45,000 --> 00:02:55,000
I had a coin at a time for particularly youngsters to have a guy named Fred Astaire to come to me because I was a type of kid.

25
00:02:55,000 --> 00:03:00,000
I didn't have the talent to dance and the same, but I had the time to go collect the money.

26
00:03:00,000 --> 00:03:10,000
What he told me at that particular time was he enjoyed us with and pressed him most of the time that we always gave a good show for the money.

27
00:03:10,000 --> 00:03:22,000
That was something to stay with me throughout my career as a public figure in the world of sports to make sure that I gave the people a very good show for the money.

28
00:03:22,000 --> 00:03:29,000
I began to develop in Harlem and wide-eyed, I would look and see what was going on.

29
00:03:29,000 --> 00:03:36,000
At that particular time, I noticed at a very young age that they had a thing called White Flight.

30
00:03:36,000 --> 00:03:49,000
It appeared that all the white folks had a meeting at night and decided that we were going to just move out of Harlem because they all started moving to the suburbs and left Harlem primarily for black people.

31
00:03:49,000 --> 00:03:51,000
What years were these?

32
00:03:51,000 --> 00:04:04,000
I was born June 5, 1945. So I would say roughly eight years, nine years into my life, these things started taking place.

33
00:04:04,000 --> 00:04:19,000
I recall actually my father while I was leaving and my father pretty much told me that it was difficult for white folks to accept the fact that most of the domesticated workers that was there to clean the house

34
00:04:19,000 --> 00:04:25,000
would have you would start to move into the apartment buildings and live as next door neighbors.

35
00:04:25,000 --> 00:04:31,000
So I guess a lot of them felt like we can't have this and they decided to leave.

36
00:04:31,000 --> 00:04:40,000
In retrospect, now he in 2013, if you would go back to Harlem, many of the ancestors of those white individuals that moved out have moved back into Harlem.

37
00:04:40,000 --> 00:04:46,000
It doesn't disappear that way in Harlem is happening all over the United States.

38
00:04:46,000 --> 00:04:56,000
But in any case, I continue to grow in New York. I got a chance to experience what the drug scene was.

39
00:04:56,000 --> 00:05:04,000
When I was a kid, the drug of choice for many individuals was a thing called King Kong. King Kong was a bootleg liquor.

40
00:05:04,000 --> 00:05:10,000
It was almost if I were to put that parallel with something modern times, I would say King Kong was like PCP.

41
00:05:10,000 --> 00:05:19,000
A lot of these individuals would drink this bootleg liquor and they would go to the roof and actually take off like they could fly and jump to their death.

42
00:05:19,000 --> 00:05:29,000
And then overnight King Kong left and this thing called Heron came in, smack mud or whatever you get to call it.

43
00:05:29,000 --> 00:05:34,000
And that's when I noticed that family started to disintegrate.

44
00:05:34,000 --> 00:05:45,000
When I say disintegrate, I mean explode in terms of all of the love and affection and the harmony that they had in the household just dissolved.

45
00:05:45,000 --> 00:05:49,000
Because at that particular time, there used to be a unit, a family unit.

46
00:05:49,000 --> 00:05:59,000
To the point where all families got together between 5'30 and 6'o'clock to have dinner, to have discussion as to what happened in school, did you do your homework?

47
00:05:59,000 --> 00:06:04,000
How did you make out of your science project? All of these things were taking place.

48
00:06:04,000 --> 00:06:09,000
And then when the drugs came in, it just disillusioned a lot of the fathers.

49
00:06:09,000 --> 00:06:15,000
Many of the fathers became, as I call them, missing an action because they stopped coming home.

50
00:06:15,000 --> 00:06:22,000
They were sprung on those drugs and left pretty much the families to be raised by the mothers.

51
00:06:22,000 --> 00:06:25,000
Mothers tried and do the best they could.

52
00:06:25,000 --> 00:06:29,000
A lot of them at that particular time had 3 or 4 or 5 kids.

53
00:06:29,000 --> 00:06:37,000
And then for the mom to try and raise those kids by themselves, it put a lot of unnecessary pressure on them.

54
00:06:37,000 --> 00:06:42,000
Some of them started to chip around with the drugs themselves. Some of them went to alcohol.

55
00:06:42,000 --> 00:06:48,000
But the bottom line was it was very difficult for them to survive economically.

56
00:06:48,000 --> 00:06:57,000
If you looked at that particular time for a black family in the United States, jointly, if they made $15,000, there was a top of the line.

57
00:06:57,000 --> 00:07:03,000
So when the fathers left, that cut income considerably.

58
00:07:03,000 --> 00:07:10,000
So then when you looked in there, closet, there was no clothes. You looked in the ice box. There was no food.

59
00:07:10,000 --> 00:07:20,000
There was anything that they had was a hand down from maybe brother that was 4 or 5 years older than them. They just would hand the clothes down.

60
00:07:20,000 --> 00:07:26,000
I began to look around in terms of what role could I play, what could I do?

61
00:07:26,000 --> 00:07:28,000
Did your family hang together during this period?

62
00:07:28,000 --> 00:07:38,000
My mother and father was strong as the rocket you brought to. My father was a shoemaker. My father was a veteran from the First World War.

63
00:07:38,000 --> 00:07:47,000
He had an entrepreneurial type of mind where he was his own man and he set up his own business and did quite well.

64
00:07:47,000 --> 00:07:52,000
My mother came in pretty much as a domesticated worker as well.

65
00:07:53,000 --> 00:08:03,000
I remember when we were young kids, my mother would take my myself from our brother at times when she used to go and clean the abortion offices, all through a Harlem.

66
00:08:03,000 --> 00:08:05,000
You know, going and cleaning the after-birth.

67
00:08:05,000 --> 00:08:09,000
And I remember I used to go snooping around just to look and see what was going on.

68
00:08:09,000 --> 00:08:15,000
And I saw some things in there that maybe I shouldn't have saw at that particular age.

69
00:08:15,000 --> 00:08:20,000
Well, you know, I went on to realize that I don't want to go into detail about it.

70
00:08:20,000 --> 00:08:35,000
But I would say with the drug trade, the deputate at the time, there was a professional type of drugs that some of these professional doctors had in the office where professional people used these drugs like entertainers,

71
00:08:35,000 --> 00:08:46,000
doctors, lawyers, or what have you. And then there was a street drug that I mentioned earlier that the heroin I was out just open for just the everyday people in the street.

72
00:08:46,000 --> 00:09:00,000
But I began to look around as I said to see what my niche was. What could I do to try and make things better for my peers, you know, the standard of life that they had to bring them up to, at least standard that we had in my household.

73
00:09:00,000 --> 00:09:05,000
And I saw a guy on TV that I was very impressed with, a white fella.

74
00:09:05,000 --> 00:09:12,000
He used to run around in a green suit and had a funny looking hat with a fella sticking out it. And they call this guy Robin Hood.

75
00:09:12,000 --> 00:09:19,000
And I began to look at Robin Hood in terms of, wow, this is a guy that I want to image myself as.

76
00:09:19,000 --> 00:09:32,000
I got it had no fear in terms of the authority figures because it appeared to me that Robin Hood split the pee in half so to speak and made it clear to himself.

77
00:09:32,000 --> 00:09:39,000
There was two laws of the land. There was God's law and there was man's law. And he made it clear that he wasn't concerned about man's law.

78
00:09:39,000 --> 00:09:47,000
He was concerned about God's law. And he did his job. And when I say man's law, I'm talking about like the sheriff nodding him, you know, the way they presented Robin Hood.

79
00:09:47,000 --> 00:09:54,000
And I like the way he carried himself. So then I began to look at what was happening in the freight trains just like this.

80
00:09:54,000 --> 00:09:57,000
This culture of the carriage would come through nodding him far.

81
00:09:57,000 --> 00:10:03,000
Well, the Yankee Stadium in the freight jobs over there was nodding him far for John Carlos.

82
00:10:03,000 --> 00:10:10,000
And I remember going over there with a couple of my buddies and told him we was going to investigate boys coming in on the trains.

83
00:10:10,000 --> 00:10:23,000
And at that particular time they were bringing in much food. They had the frozen freight trains coming out with succotash and starting to develop the frozen food products.

84
00:10:23,000 --> 00:10:32,000
They had textiles that was coming through. And my other two was to go and capture these goods, you might say.

85
00:10:32,000 --> 00:10:39,000
And I remember my buddies telling me, man, we're going to have fat pockets. And I said, no, this is not for us. This is for the people in the community that don't have.

86
00:10:39,000 --> 00:10:46,000
You know, and a lot of them that I was talking to at that particular time, they wasn't doing as well as the individuals that I was talking about.

87
00:10:46,000 --> 00:10:55,000
So it was self-serving for them to stock up their houses with clothes and food and so forth as well.

88
00:10:55,000 --> 00:11:04,000
And at the same time, I had to remind myself that my father, my mother, was starch Americans.

89
00:11:04,000 --> 00:11:09,000
I mean, when I say Americans, I mean to the hill that my father served in the First World War.

90
00:11:09,000 --> 00:11:20,000
He was proud of his service in the war. My mother was, you know, a farmer coming to the United States and proud to be an American citizen and just believed in doing things the right way.

91
00:11:20,000 --> 00:11:27,000
So when I'm breaking the law by hitting these freight trains and so forth, they were more concerned about mans law.

92
00:11:27,000 --> 00:11:38,000
And I was more concerned about God's law, but yet still I still had love, respect for my parents, not to let my father know what I was doing and to safeguard myself,

93
00:11:38,000 --> 00:11:43,000
to make sure they didn't get back to my father. That I was breaking into these freight trains.

94
00:11:44,000 --> 00:11:51,000
As I began to get older, I heard about this guy swimming the English Channel.

95
00:11:51,000 --> 00:11:59,000
At that particular time, radio was our TV. We used to listen to Johnny Dalland, Dick Trace, you know, all these guys on the radio.

96
00:11:59,000 --> 00:12:03,000
And I heard them mention this guy swimming the English Channel.

97
00:12:03,000 --> 00:12:09,000
Yeah, as I stated, I didn't know what the English Channel was. I knew that he was in the water.

98
00:12:10,000 --> 00:12:21,000
I knew that I was probably the best bathtub swimmer in Harlem. I would swim quite a bit in the Harlem River, lost quite a few friends in the Harlem River.

99
00:12:21,000 --> 00:12:26,000
But you ever swimming in an organized swimming pool?

100
00:12:26,000 --> 00:12:35,000
No, I never got a chance to swim in a pool, but I developed this thought in my mind that I was going to swim the English Channel.

101
00:12:35,000 --> 00:12:41,000
And I remember asking my father, said, pop the U-swimming. He said, yes, son, just like a rock straight to the bottom.

102
00:12:41,000 --> 00:12:48,000
But I asked him, I said, daddy, if they swim in the English Channel, did they swim with a knife in their mouth? What about the sharks?

103
00:12:48,000 --> 00:12:53,000
I said, and when they have to go to the bathroom, how do they go to the bathroom if they swim in?

104
00:12:53,000 --> 00:12:58,000
You know, because I never knew that they'd come out of the water and do what they had to do, and they'd drop back and water and they carry on.

105
00:12:58,000 --> 00:13:10,000
But I had the mind said that I was inquisitive enough that I wanted to know how you do this, how they set the tide to a compass to go.

106
00:13:10,000 --> 00:13:17,000
What did they get, daddy? Did they get a trophy? Did they get money? Did they get recognition? And he told me, say, son, they get it all.

107
00:13:17,000 --> 00:13:23,000
So he told me he would go and research about the sharks and the whole nine yards, and he would get back to me.

108
00:13:23,000 --> 00:13:29,000
Well, in the meantime, when he went to do that, they came back on the radio again and they started talking about the Olympic Games.

109
00:13:29,000 --> 00:13:37,000
And, daddy, what's the Olympic Games? Well, he said, son, that's when all the great nations come together and they bring their best athletes together.

110
00:13:37,000 --> 00:13:44,000
He said, it's like war games to see who's more physical and more mentally fit to put their best foot forward.

111
00:13:44,000 --> 00:13:48,000
And I said to him, I said, well, daddy, did they have swimming? He said, yes.

112
00:13:48,000 --> 00:13:53,000
I said, well, daddy, did they ever have a black swimmer to represent the United States? And he said, no, son.

113
00:13:53,000 --> 00:13:58,000
And I said, well, daddy, I'm going to be the first black to represent America as a swimmer.

114
00:13:58,000 --> 00:14:04,000
And I developed this in my mind and my heart. And this is something that I really want to do.

115
00:14:04,000 --> 00:14:09,000
And one day, my father, I guess maybe I've gone maybe 10 months a year.

116
00:14:09,000 --> 00:14:14,000
And my father saw that I picked this thing up in my mind and my heart was running with it.

117
00:14:14,000 --> 00:14:17,000
And he said to me, he said, son, we need to have a talk.

118
00:14:17,000 --> 00:14:24,000
And I can look at the expression in his face like it was a painful thing in this talk that we was going to have.

119
00:14:24,000 --> 00:14:34,000
And he was going to have to give me. And I said, what's that, daddy? And he said to me, he said, son, he said, you're going to have to, you know, get rid of that thought about you going to your Olympics as a swimmer.

120
00:14:34,000 --> 00:14:43,000
Why, daddy, what do you mean? He said, well, son, my understanding of the swimmer has to swim three, four times a day, train. Where would you train?

121
00:14:43,000 --> 00:14:49,000
He said to me, he said, you can't go to the Harlem River and train. You lose your friends every summer.

122
00:14:49,000 --> 00:14:54,000
He said, you can't go to colonial pool. That was the public pool where the black kids go to every day.

123
00:14:54,000 --> 00:14:57,000
So you can't go there. People too many people trying to cook love.

124
00:14:57,000 --> 00:15:03,000
You can't go to the ocean. The water is too rough. And I'm saying to him, son, what daddy? I'm joined a club.

125
00:15:03,000 --> 00:15:09,000
And he said, oh, and you can't join a club. And I said, what daddy? We can't afford it. He said, oh, no, we can afford it.

126
00:15:09,000 --> 00:15:16,000
Well, why can't I join? And then he put his hand on like that and he rubbed his hand. And when he did it, I thought he had a bug bite or something.

127
00:15:16,000 --> 00:15:20,000
And he said, no, son, because of the color of your skin.

128
00:15:20,000 --> 00:15:32,000
And before I could die just that and say, because of the color of my skin, there was another pool pool up there, not too far from the other born ballroom where my commercial assassinated called high-bridge pool.

129
00:15:32,000 --> 00:15:41,000
And that was the white area at that particular time. And my father mentioned to me and my father didn't go into pool that much.

130
00:15:41,000 --> 00:15:49,000
But he knew what was going on. And he said to me, he said, son, he said, when you and your friends work the high-bridge pool and you jump into the water, what happened?

131
00:15:49,000 --> 00:16:01,000
And you know, just seconds, you flash back in your mind and you remember, as soon as you hit the water, all the white mothers would jump up and call their kids, Bobby, Billy, Ricky, Betty, Judy, get out the water.

132
00:16:01,000 --> 00:16:11,000
Get out the water, get out the water, hurry up. And it was very complexing for me for the simple reason that in one sense they didn't want to be me.

133
00:16:11,000 --> 00:16:20,000
They didn't want their kids like someone's going to roll off me onto them. And in another sense, they was putting all sorts of lotion on them, laying in the sun, trying to get look like me.

134
00:16:20,000 --> 00:16:30,000
So I was really confused about the whole scenario. And then my father said to me, he said, son, let me ask you this question, are you going to quit?

135
00:16:30,000 --> 00:16:42,000
And I said to him, I said, no, Danny, I'll find another way. Well, by working into those freight trains and showing you how God worked, that was my vehicle to track and feel.

136
00:16:42,000 --> 00:16:54,000
Because we had two detectives in Harlem. I missed the Lester and Mr. Bryant. They were out of a 32nd precinct right there in 135th Street.

137
00:16:54,000 --> 00:17:04,000
They knew my father because my father used to have the poker game on weekends with baseball players, Jackie Robinson, all those people who didn't even play, they would all come together.

138
00:17:04,000 --> 00:17:18,000
And I remember my father having a conversation with those two detectives. And they were telling my father that there's been some break-ins over the freight yards and they think I had something to do with it.

139
00:17:18,000 --> 00:17:28,000
And I was telling my dad that you need to talk to John. And my father stopped them. He actually put his hand up saying, nah, you need to talk to him.

140
00:17:28,000 --> 00:17:39,000
And in that particular time, I was over McCun兵 Park at a PL track meet. And I went over there to run the track meet. I was over there to get some new converse sneakers.

141
00:17:39,000 --> 00:17:47,000
And all the kids had new converse sneakers. And my father was a shoe maker. So I didn't get a chance to get the new shoes. My old man would make shoes.

142
00:17:47,000 --> 00:17:55,000
So in order for me to get some converse, I would have to go over there because the kids that were running, they would take their new sneakers and so forth and put in their pants and roll them up.

143
00:17:55,000 --> 00:18:02,000
Well, me and my buddies never had no new sneakers. So we would go over there and take our old shoes and leave the shoes and take their sneakers.

144
00:18:02,000 --> 00:18:14,000
So when he came that particular day, they'd circle the whole park and had cop cars around the park and they came in and they found me and I was with two of my buddies and they told my buddies, go sit up against the fence.

145
00:18:14,000 --> 00:18:29,000
And they took me into the infield of the track. And Mr. Luster is about six feet and Mr. Brown was about six seven. Mr. Brown was a big guy.

146
00:18:29,000 --> 00:18:33,000
Are these African-American detectives? Yes, sir.

147
00:18:33,000 --> 00:18:44,000
And Mr. Brown said to me, Mr. Luster had something to tell you. Mr. Luster said to me, he said, let me tell you something, Johnny, it's been some break ins.

148
00:18:44,000 --> 00:18:53,000
And we think we know who's doing it. And then it leaned down into my face real close and said, we can't do anything until we catch him.

149
00:18:53,000 --> 00:19:03,000
And we're going to catch him. And then he said, but I have something else I want to tell you. And I looked at him and said, what's that? And he said, you have a talent.

150
00:19:03,000 --> 00:19:13,000
I have a talent. What talent do I have? And he said, you as a runner because the police chase from the Bronx over into Holland River houses.

151
00:19:13,000 --> 00:19:21,000
They catch some of my partners, but they could never catch me. And these were like the Irish police and someone were poorly, but they could roll.

152
00:19:21,000 --> 00:19:28,000
I mean, when I say they could roll, they could run. I mean, gun belt, night stick didn't bother them. They just truck it.

153
00:19:28,000 --> 00:19:40,000
So when he said I was a runner, I kind of smirked like that. And before I could pull myself back, Mr. Brown smacked me upside my head. And when he smacked me head, fingers landed over head.

154
00:19:40,000 --> 00:19:46,000
And that's how big his hands were. And he said, don't you disrespect Mr. Lester. I said, Mr. Brown, I'm not disrespecting him.

155
00:19:46,000 --> 00:20:00,000
I said, but he said that I'm a runner. Everybody in neighborhood runs. And when I said that I had something in mind, specifically based on an incident that happened with my mother, my mother began the working BWH through at night.

156
00:20:00,000 --> 00:20:14,000
And I recall my mother going out one night to work. And I guess about an hour she came back and I stuck. I was all torn and she legs was bleeding. And kid came up and grabbed her purse.

157
00:20:14,000 --> 00:20:27,000
And I guess she was holding onto the person. He drugged down. Well, she got back up and she came home. And you're quite naturally all the men, me, my brother, my father, everybody was upset.

158
00:20:27,000 --> 00:20:44,000
And my mother, she saw it saw it right. We get some a cure cone and we put it under some bandage. And then she held up her purse. She said, but I got my purse back. So when I'm talking about as a runner, I'm saying my mother's a runner. Everybody in the neighborhood is a runner. And they told me, Sonata Johnny, you're special.

159
00:20:44,000 --> 00:20:54,000
And they gave me a number to the New York Pioneer Club to ask me to call a guy by the name of Joe Yancy. He was the head master. You might say, of the track program.

160
00:20:54,000 --> 00:21:08,000
And I went down there. It was a, it was a new experience for me. How did you at this point? I think I was like 13, 14. And I went in and I didn't have any track gear. I didn't know what track gear was.

161
00:21:08,000 --> 00:21:20,000
I went in. I had some quarter van shoes, some, some jeans. And they asked me where is my gear. And I looked at them and I said, first of all, what's gear? And I said, Mrs. All I had.

162
00:21:20,000 --> 00:21:28,000
He said, what do you run? I said, distant because when I went out to the track that day and Mr. Lesson, Mr. Brown caught a whole of me.

163
00:21:28,000 --> 00:21:37,000
What they told me was get on the track and run until we take the stop. Well, they forgot about me. I'm going to run. I'm going to run. Run at track 50 times.

164
00:21:37,000 --> 00:21:48,000
So when the guy asked me, what do I run? I'm a distance runner. So he told me, he said, well, he had these guys over here. The older guys that were the day they were running. It's like 660s.

165
00:21:48,000 --> 00:22:01,000
Jimmy Brown and guys like that. Frankie Barn. They out there running 660s. And I didn't know what it's 660 was. I didn't know what the fall 40 to 20 put together. You know, 660.

166
00:22:01,000 --> 00:22:11,000
And they were running five of them. Well, they had run one when I got there. And when I was talking to Mr. Yancy and Mr. Levy.

167
00:22:11,000 --> 00:22:20,000
And they told me to go. So I got in there and I started running when I'm down the first two I won. I was beating my soul.

168
00:22:20,000 --> 00:22:29,000
They was doing a new defense mind wasn't I won. The next one I come back to third when I won last one. I'm running and they had something called the beer.

169
00:22:29,000 --> 00:22:38,000
I didn't know what the beer was. And that's total fatigue. I wasn't in shape to doing it. I never trained. I was just running off my natural ability on this last one.

170
00:22:38,000 --> 00:22:46,000
I was just running and I was like they had a sniper on the roof and he just shot me. And I just exploded and fell out.

171
00:22:46,000 --> 00:22:58,000
And I remember them taking me out the army. My partner that was down there. They took me out the army. And we were walking on a 141st Street coming back up to Lennox Avenue.

172
00:22:58,000 --> 00:23:04,000
And I remember when it was helping me and it was cold and snow on the ground. And I remember I was coming back through.

173
00:23:04,000 --> 00:23:11,000
You know, I'm starting to get myself together. And I had one older guy. I said, man, who the hell that kid think he is?

174
00:23:11,000 --> 00:23:19,000
I think he's just going to be able to come out here and run against us and do the things he's doing. And I was kind of like looking at him like, what?

175
00:23:19,000 --> 00:23:25,000
And the other guy said to him, man, I don't know who that kid is. But I think everybody going to know who you who you are soon.

176
00:23:25,000 --> 00:23:30,000
And I remember telling the other guy, say, man, I think I'm ready. We can go back and finish that race now.

177
00:23:30,000 --> 00:23:40,000
And the rest was pretty much like stair step in terms of my career because they begin to see me running the meats in high school.

178
00:23:41,000 --> 00:23:49,000
I noticed that a lot of guys didn't have the confidence that I had in my abilities or in their abilities.

179
00:23:49,000 --> 00:23:57,000
I began to excel based on what Mr. Fred Astaire said about giving a good show for the money.

180
00:23:57,000 --> 00:24:04,000
I remember my first competition. We had great cotton sweats, the old great cotton sweats.

181
00:24:05,000 --> 00:24:14,000
And I remember I got a magic marker and I pulled my sweat pants off and I wrote a big J on one of my buttocks and a big C on the other buttocks.

182
00:24:14,000 --> 00:24:23,000
My father said, man, what are you doing? I said, man, I'm putting J C on this. So when they see me jogging, they're going to know this name, J C, J C, J C, Johnny Carlos, Johnny Carlos.

183
00:24:23,000 --> 00:24:28,000
And I went on and built the reputation from high school.

184
00:24:28,000 --> 00:24:31,000
Was there a decent track program at your high school?

185
00:24:31,000 --> 00:24:43,000
Well, we didn't have a track as well. We used to train running the hallways. We'd run the hall and open up the cafeteria doors and run around tables and shoot back down the hall.

186
00:24:43,000 --> 00:24:52,000
And then when we had a time trial to see who was going to go to the Penn Relays, we used to be able to go to Franklin Roosevelt Drive on 96 and First Ave.

187
00:24:52,000 --> 00:24:58,000
We would run the ballwalk there so to speak to see who was going to make the team.

188
00:24:58,000 --> 00:25:08,000
No, we didn't have anything easy. And then I might state that I didn't particularly care for track and feel. I still wanted to be a swimmer.

189
00:25:08,000 --> 00:25:19,000
I went to Frederick Douglass junior high school. And I guess because I was such a gangster kid, you might say.

190
00:25:19,000 --> 00:25:30,000
Because I pretty much ran the school in my time there, my tenure there. And I didn't get a chance to run, excuse me, for the school track program.

191
00:25:30,000 --> 00:25:37,000
And I wanted to go to a certain school high school because they had a swimming program.

192
00:25:37,000 --> 00:25:42,000
But this particular day I think I cut out of school, played hooky that didn't go to school.

193
00:25:42,000 --> 00:25:51,000
And we fill out the paperwork to go to school and they changed my paperwork for me to go to Harron High School on 59th and 10th FAT.

194
00:25:51,000 --> 00:26:03,000
And told me that they had a swim program in the school. And when I found out the day changed the paperwork and I'm giving my paper to someone going to Harron High School, I don't want to go to Harron High School.

195
00:26:03,000 --> 00:26:11,000
Why would you do it? What is this? This is what you put down. And my boys tell me, man, it's going to be all right. They got a great swim program down there. You're going to do well.

196
00:26:11,000 --> 00:26:19,000
When I got down, they didn't have a pool much more swim program. And then I didn't run track for the school.

197
00:26:19,000 --> 00:26:21,000
So why did they send you down there?

198
00:26:21,000 --> 00:26:35,000
Well, they sent me there because they wanted me on the track program. But they didn't have a swim program. And they wouldn't allow me to get on the track program because I wasn't one of the right students, you might say.

199
00:26:35,000 --> 00:26:54,000
I was still in the Doug element. So I never got a chance to run for Harron High School. And then eventually I left Harron High School and transferred to a machine of metal trades on 96th Street.

200
00:26:54,000 --> 00:26:56,000
I'm going to take a little pause here.

201
00:26:56,000 --> 00:27:06,000
This gave me honor. That's yeah, I think it was. It went to the archives because I came back and gave a speech for the Board of Education, for the Prince of Wolves, I guess.

202
00:27:06,000 --> 00:27:18,000
And they went to women said, I'll find out you went to school. Yeah, she dug up some stuff. Board tears in my eyes because I forgot about a lot of the guys. And she made a collage, all the pictures and so forth.

203
00:27:18,000 --> 00:27:24,000
So this is machine metal trades and you transferred there and what what year were you in school?

204
00:27:24,000 --> 00:27:29,000
Man, don't give me the line. But somewhere in high school. Yeah, yeah.

205
00:27:29,000 --> 00:27:33,000
And how did things change once you once you went over there?

206
00:27:33,000 --> 00:27:45,000
Well, this got better for me based on the fact that I some of the guys I knew older guys in my neighborhood had gone to school there and they were involved in the track program.

207
00:27:45,000 --> 00:27:57,000
And I remember we had one group picture. And I was on the team. I was probably one and younger guys on the team, but one of the bigger guys as well.

208
00:27:57,000 --> 00:28:14,000
And we took our first team picture. We had our street pants on and we had the school jersey on and I felt like I was a part of something at that time, you know, to run with guys that I knew and wanted to excel and something.

209
00:28:14,000 --> 00:28:28,000
Once we got out there and gotten involved in the competition, I realized early that those guys didn't have the same awareness of the abilities as I had of my abilities.

210
00:28:28,000 --> 00:28:40,000
You know, they didn't have the confidence to think they can beat a lot of guys. And tracking field when you first start track or feel it's it's a novice novice is individuals that have never won anything.

211
00:28:40,000 --> 00:28:53,000
They have opened individuals they have won a medal. They have won something in the past. And we went in and we went in as novice. And we were sitting on the floor. They bring us all the novice kids out and they sit us on the floor.

212
00:28:53,000 --> 00:29:00,000
And as we were sitting on the floor, the open guys, the ones that had excelled in the past, they were running their races.

213
00:29:00,000 --> 00:29:13,000
You know, I remember looking at my guys and they were like horrified that this man we can never beat these guys. Look how fast y'all. And I remember telling them, say man they only look fast because we're sitting here watching them.

214
00:29:13,000 --> 00:29:28,000
We will be just as good as them when we get out there and run against them. And another thing I noticed that they had songs about boys high, do we Clinton, Rhythmas, they had no songs from me at Machina Metal Traits.

215
00:29:28,000 --> 00:29:38,000
So when we got up and we ran our memo told them I said, if y'all bring me this baton 30 yards and back to the last guy we'll win.

216
00:29:38,000 --> 00:29:53,000
Because I'm going to catch you up without there. And we went on and we broke the record and our heat. And I never forget we went to lunch at the delicatessen store right there on Amsterdam Avenue by the armory.

217
00:29:53,000 --> 00:30:05,000
And we went there and we ate by the time we come back that afternoon to run the finals that created a song about Machina Metal Traits. And I'm nodding them saying man they're singing about us, they're singing about us.

218
00:30:05,000 --> 00:30:16,000
So that was a start of us having a legendary reputation there. And we went on and we won the final. We broke the record again.

219
00:30:16,000 --> 00:30:27,000
But when my legacy started in track and field and the 16th Street Armory I ran extremely well indoors. But that wasn't the racists.

220
00:30:27,000 --> 00:30:41,000
The racists outside after the track meet was over because I would race against all and winners outdoors and actually having an opportunity to say, look man I race you.

221
00:30:41,000 --> 00:30:51,000
And you got all your medals because a lot of the guys they took so much pride in their awards they pinned them on the jacket and medals that I won I used to give them to the girls.

222
00:30:51,000 --> 00:31:04,000
It was a competition that I like it wasn't about the award. If I got an award I got an award because I want the show that I was there. You had to win something to let them know you was there.

223
00:31:04,000 --> 00:31:17,000
If I took 30 it didn't matter. But when I got outside of the armory that's when the real competition started because I would give a guy say man I'm going to give you four call lengths on Beachy by three.

224
00:31:17,000 --> 00:31:29,000
And it was extraordinary because I had as many people outside watching these races as was inside. They didn't even give me give us a formality we had to go through the process indoors.

225
00:31:29,000 --> 00:31:35,000
But everybody was waiting for after the track meet the serious races. I was like street ball taking a break.

226
00:31:35,000 --> 00:31:51,000
Last night I was there and that's all they were talking about. Say Johnny you know we were just little kids but we heard legend we heard legend a lot of the younger guys they never met me and they looking at me like I'm a living legend you know and it kind of like freaky out.

227
00:31:51,000 --> 00:32:01,000
You know you guys looking at you like that and then the head stories that they were saying about your peers that was there with you things that they were saying about me different type of thing.

228
00:32:01,000 --> 00:32:08,000
I never knew what they were saying. I just tried this out last night. But that's what built the legend in John Colors.

229
00:32:08,000 --> 00:32:11,000
Do you remember that song from a scene in the middle trades at all?

230
00:32:11,000 --> 00:32:20,000
No man I can't remember. It wasn't a fling-voin song with something had to do with Marilyn Monroe's chest or something like that.

231
00:32:20,000 --> 00:32:42,000
But it was a strong song. But what I was trying to say relative to me looking at track and feel I begin to go to another level and track and feel like what track and feel really means to me and not so much about me getting start them.

232
00:32:42,000 --> 00:32:52,000
But what I can use track and feel is a springboard too. I begin to realize that the better I'm perfecting my game the better I can speak.

233
00:32:52,000 --> 00:33:00,000
The better I can have a platform to do what I need to do in life because I never forgot about what happened on that exam.

234
00:33:00,000 --> 00:33:06,000
I never forgot about the drugs. I never forgot about the domesticated work. I never forgot about white flight.

235
00:33:06,000 --> 00:33:13,000
And then at the same time I'm starting to learn about prejudices and racism and that kind of thing.

236
00:33:13,000 --> 00:33:22,000
So now I'm really looking at this thing in terms of me being able to use track and feel as a vehicle.

237
00:33:22,000 --> 00:33:29,000
The better I got the more I was able to have a platform to give my message off.

238
00:33:29,000 --> 00:33:37,000
And these days everybody wants to play ball and get out. This is what everyone thinks is the magic ticket.

239
00:33:37,000 --> 00:33:41,000
And those days were sports seen as a ticket out?

240
00:33:41,000 --> 00:33:46,000
You have to look back in those days and look at it for what it was.

241
00:33:46,000 --> 00:33:56,000
When you sit back and think about what was happening back let's say 60, 70, 80 years ago.

242
00:33:56,000 --> 00:34:06,000
It was like this in the area if they had black kids or minority kids and they had white kids while the white part of the town had a swimming pool.

243
00:34:06,000 --> 00:34:14,000
Then in black area never had a swimming pool. People never had a swimming pool. But what they would give us in place is a basketball court.

244
00:34:14,000 --> 00:34:21,000
So when you sit back you think about all the superstar basketball players back in the day, Bill Russell, Elgin Bell and the guys before them.

245
00:34:21,000 --> 00:34:29,000
They became superstars merely because that was what they gave them a post to giving them the standard with all kids,

246
00:34:29,000 --> 00:34:35,000
and then the summer to be in a swimming pool. But they didn't want us in the water. And the same thing fell.

247
00:34:35,000 --> 00:34:42,000
So everybody was doing a thing in terms of let me perfect my game.

248
00:34:42,000 --> 00:34:48,000
But it wasn't my game to say I'm playing basketball because I want to be an NBA star.

249
00:34:48,000 --> 00:34:52,000
I'm playing because I enjoy the game and I'm perfect in my game and I'm good at it.

250
00:34:52,000 --> 00:34:58,000
Now people start to come and look. But then on the same time the people that gave them the puck,

251
00:34:58,000 --> 00:35:04,000
they began to look at them in terms of economic growth and economic gain because now we can take these kids.

252
00:35:04,000 --> 00:35:07,000
Now we didn't know that they was going to build their game like that.

253
00:35:07,000 --> 00:35:12,000
And then you know the Rutgers tournament that they have in New York,

254
00:35:12,000 --> 00:35:20,000
it was so many individual kids that had to become street merchants, hustling in the street,

255
00:35:20,000 --> 00:35:27,000
that had phenomenal basketball talent. The pros wanted them.

256
00:35:27,000 --> 00:35:31,000
They looked at the pros like, man, this is my game. You're going to change my game.

257
00:35:31,000 --> 00:35:35,000
And you can't wave no money. I'm making as much money as you try to offer me.

258
00:35:35,000 --> 00:35:43,000
So that era, they looked at Rutgers and turned to saying, oh, these kids here have a different sense about them.

259
00:35:43,000 --> 00:35:47,000
Like you know when Wilk Chamon came down, Elgin Bella came down,

260
00:35:47,000 --> 00:35:51,000
all of them would go to Rutgers tournament and they had their greatness at bottom.

261
00:35:51,000 --> 00:35:56,000
But they found these raw natural kids had equal greatness.

262
00:35:56,000 --> 00:36:03,000
But you know, still those kids are saying, man, you can't tell me enough of it because that's my rose rice parked over there.

263
00:36:03,000 --> 00:36:07,000
Because they got involved in the street merchantry.

264
00:36:07,000 --> 00:36:15,000
It was all about dollars. But with your dollars, you want to give me dollars to control me in the way I play ball.

265
00:36:15,000 --> 00:36:20,000
Well, my dollars I'm free enough to be my own man and play ball the way I see fit to play ball.

266
00:36:20,000 --> 00:36:24,000
And that's the way I grew. And now, in modern times, things have changed.

267
00:36:24,000 --> 00:36:29,000
Everyone wants to just be focused on the dollar. I don't see nothing about what's happening in my community.

268
00:36:29,000 --> 00:36:32,000
I'm not concerned about my fellow man.

269
00:36:32,000 --> 00:36:37,000
None of those things are taking place now. The bottom line is the almighty dollar.

270
00:36:37,000 --> 00:36:44,000
All the drugs that you see in basketball, football, or baseball, or track and field.

271
00:36:44,000 --> 00:36:49,000
They put that secondary in terms of they should have been moving on this long time ago.

272
00:36:49,000 --> 00:36:56,000
They know the difference in when Hank Aaron and Willie Mays and then was playing ball the post to the modern day ball player.

273
00:36:56,000 --> 00:37:04,000
Now, they knew what Jesse on his dead, Tommy Smith or Liam's or John Collins did, opposed to what these kids are doing now.

274
00:37:04,000 --> 00:37:09,000
But they said, we'll turn our head to it because we're bringing people through the third style.

275
00:37:09,000 --> 00:37:12,000
We make money. We get bigger TV contracts.

276
00:37:12,000 --> 00:37:16,000
All the sponsors want to come in now.

277
00:37:16,000 --> 00:37:22,000
But then you look at sports right now and you say, wow, the sponsorship is not as great anymore.

278
00:37:22,000 --> 00:37:25,000
And tell the Olympics are rolling around. Why is it great anymore?

279
00:37:25,000 --> 00:37:32,000
Because I don't want to sponsor something and then pick up the next day and find out that these guys are using drugs and tonnish my product.

280
00:37:32,000 --> 00:37:35,000
So they're not jumping out there as much anymore.

281
00:37:35,000 --> 00:37:42,000
Anytime they jump out there as the Olympics, like Finns is right now, Mr. Putin, President of Russia.

282
00:37:42,000 --> 00:37:47,000
He's talking about, you know, I don't want gays in the games.

283
00:37:47,000 --> 00:37:49,000
Well, he's ridiculous.

284
00:37:49,000 --> 00:37:53,000
If he thinks that the gays are not involved in society and something is wrong with him.

285
00:37:53,000 --> 00:38:01,000
Now, if they want to get into a moral clause, then my whole line to them is, when you become God and you show me that you're God,

286
00:38:01,000 --> 00:38:04,000
then you can be a moral figure over these individuals.

287
00:38:04,000 --> 00:38:08,000
But tell them, you just like me, you can't step into place of God.

288
00:38:08,000 --> 00:38:11,000
Say, because this person is this way, that person is that way.

289
00:38:11,000 --> 00:38:14,000
They shouldn't be allowed to do this. They shouldn't be allowed to do that.

290
00:38:14,000 --> 00:38:19,000
And then I sit back and look at the Olympic Committee and I say shame on you.

291
00:38:19,000 --> 00:38:26,000
Shame on you because in 1936, Hitler said, I don't want Jews and I don't want blacks on the team.

292
00:38:26,000 --> 00:38:31,000
The Olympic Committee stepped up there and said, oh, wait a minute, Mr. Hitler, you need to take a seat on this.

293
00:38:31,000 --> 00:38:46,000
But when they went to Germany, Hitler still stepped in and they still buckled and gave in to the fact that they took those young Jews, fellers off the team and replaced them because Hitler was against the Jews.

294
00:38:46,000 --> 00:38:53,000
Now, they had the same responsibility to step up to the plate to tell Mr. Putin and I say, God forbid.

295
00:38:53,000 --> 00:39:00,000
And here's a hypothetical statement. If you say in both, it's to come out.

296
00:39:00,000 --> 00:39:07,000
Are any noted figure in the sports world right now, it's to come out and say, I'm gay.

297
00:39:07,000 --> 00:39:19,000
And this is hypothetical. But if this guy said, I'm gay, do you think that the Olympic Committee would let Mr. Putin tell, saying both, that he can't run into Olympic Games because of his sexual preference?

298
00:39:19,000 --> 00:39:26,000
The Olympic Committee would tell Mr. Putin, you better go take a seat somewhere because he's the one that's selling the tickets.

299
00:39:26,000 --> 00:39:34,000
But for them to go and do this and sit on their thumbs and allow him to do this, sub-sert, especially at this day and time.

300
00:39:34,000 --> 00:39:41,000
But these are the issues that we have to deal with and these are the issues that these young athletes are going to have to be confronted with later on down the line.

301
00:39:41,000 --> 00:39:46,000
There's no neutrality in this. You can't say, man, I'm a right-wing defense on this.

302
00:39:46,000 --> 00:39:53,000
I'll see you with something or you'll against it. And if you're not going to take one side of the other, you're going to lose respect of your peers.

303
00:39:53,000 --> 00:40:01,000
You can show that you don't really have respect for yourself when you can't make a decision at a crucial situation such as that.

304
00:40:01,000 --> 00:40:05,000
Did you see the athletes speaking up on this, or do you think they will?

305
00:40:05,000 --> 00:40:11,000
Let me take this. I think the athletes have a lot of concern about these issues.

306
00:40:11,000 --> 00:40:21,000
But I think it's a matter of courage because you have to have courage because people are more concerned not about right, but they're concerned about repercussions.

307
00:40:21,000 --> 00:40:30,000
And they have to throw a repercussion to the win and do what's necessary because when you make a statement, it's not the statement that you make it is not for you.

308
00:40:30,000 --> 00:40:36,000
It's for your kids and your kids, kids and their kids to make it a better world for them coming down the line.

309
00:40:36,000 --> 00:40:44,000
I can't change what happened in 1936. I can't make an immediate change what's going to happen in 2013.

310
00:40:44,000 --> 00:40:56,000
For instance, I couldn't make an immediate change for what happened in 1968. But here we are in 2013. It made a significant change now relative to the way people think.

311
00:40:56,000 --> 00:41:01,000
It's better for my kids now. It's going to be better for their kids now.

312
00:41:01,000 --> 00:41:07,000
These individuals, I can't tell them that you should boycott because I don't agree with the boycott no more.

313
00:41:07,000 --> 00:41:11,000
And the reason I don't agree with the boycott is for two simple reasons.

314
00:41:11,000 --> 00:41:16,000
Because I equated the boycott parallel with an embargo against the nation.

315
00:41:16,000 --> 00:41:23,000
When we put an embargo against the nation, the government don't get hurt. The people of that nation get hurt.

316
00:41:23,000 --> 00:41:30,000
The government is still doing business. They still make money. Now on the other side, the boycott of the Olympic Games.

317
00:41:30,000 --> 00:41:38,000
The Olympic people don't get hurt. Two elements, which are two most important elements, those are the ones that get hurt.

318
00:41:38,000 --> 00:41:46,000
The spectators, because they never get the chances he, the greatest, perform. The athletes get hurt.

319
00:41:46,000 --> 00:41:51,000
Because they train all their lives to perform and show their whiz and they don't have an opportunity.

320
00:41:52,000 --> 00:42:00,000
So what I suggested to them is, hey man, I would suggest that you evaluate the circumstance of which you involved in.

321
00:42:00,000 --> 00:42:10,000
Research the circumstance which you involved in. Search your soul and search your moral fiber to see whether you have conviction enough to bring your courage up.

322
00:42:10,000 --> 00:42:18,000
I say, I'm going to do with floats my boat. It's not about what John Collins told him to do. It's not about me telling him this is my history.

323
00:42:18,000 --> 00:42:27,000
It's about whether you have enough in you to search out and find or just causing these things and stand fast to which you believe in.

324
00:42:27,000 --> 00:42:33,000
Whatever floats they boat. That's what they're going to have to do because that's what they're going to have to live with.

325
00:42:33,000 --> 00:42:38,000
I want to go back and catch up with the chronology. Let me ask you just one question first since we're on.

326
00:42:38,000 --> 00:42:41,000
We're back.

327
00:42:41,000 --> 00:42:48,000
And this goes to what you were saying about the athletes, getting the chance to show their wares.

328
00:42:48,000 --> 00:42:53,000
But you all in 68, you were willing to not run that year. Right?

329
00:42:53,000 --> 00:42:56,000
Because of wanting to make a statement and what you believed in.

330
00:42:56,000 --> 00:42:59,000
How difficult was that? I think you've got that.

331
00:42:59,000 --> 00:43:05,000
Well, it wasn't difficult for me at all. It wasn't difficult for me at all because I leave a way to the Olympic Games as a track meet.

332
00:43:05,000 --> 00:43:13,000
You haven't met in many track meets. But the bottom line is whether we can make a statement for society.

333
00:43:13,000 --> 00:43:18,000
I feel like you know, meadows are great.

334
00:43:18,000 --> 00:43:22,000
What meadows are nowhere near close to what life is all about.

335
00:43:22,000 --> 00:43:28,000
Now, for instance, you know, a lot of people was upset with Jimmy Carter when Jimmy Carter boycotted against the Russians and the Olympics.

336
00:43:28,000 --> 00:43:37,000
Oh, he shouldn't have did it. He shouldn't have did it. But Jimmy Carter's philosophy was that I feel that life is far more valuable than Olympic medals.

337
00:43:37,000 --> 00:43:46,000
Only difference that with me in that 45-year span is I began to look at who is the sacrificial lambs.

338
00:43:46,000 --> 00:43:55,000
The athletes and the ones that hurt the spectators and the ones that hurt and the powers to be that we really the one that we try to get their attention to had them,

339
00:43:55,000 --> 00:44:01,000
to have some compassion and consideration to change their ways. They're still making their money.

340
00:44:01,000 --> 00:44:08,000
The Liberal Committee still selling sponsorship. They still sign a multi-million dollar contract for TV rights.

341
00:44:08,000 --> 00:44:16,000
They still selling popcorn and crack rejects and hot dogs and Coca-Cola's in every form.

342
00:44:16,000 --> 00:44:21,000
When you boycott the games, you've forgotten cause.

343
00:44:21,000 --> 00:44:28,000
Just by the grace of God, well, I said, what happened to us in Mexico City was a spiritual thing. God stepped in.

344
00:44:28,000 --> 00:44:35,000
Everything fell right. Like I stated earlier, this is the first time that games televised universal in this planet.

345
00:44:35,000 --> 00:44:42,000
This is the first time the game was televised in color. This is the first time the game was held in a thorough-world nation.

346
00:44:42,000 --> 00:44:47,000
All of these things culminated with happening on that victory stand at that time.

347
00:44:47,000 --> 00:44:55,000
And I can go father to tell you when I was a kid on that same street I was telling you Lennox have, when I was seven, eight years old, God gave me a vision and showed me in a arena.

348
00:44:55,000 --> 00:45:00,000
I didn't know what the stadium was. I didn't know what the podium was. I was on a box.

349
00:45:00,000 --> 00:45:06,000
And I went to wave and I'm right handed. When I went to wave to the people, I put my left hand up the wave.

350
00:45:06,000 --> 00:45:10,000
And before I can get my hand up high, my hand was by the same way it was with that glove.

351
00:45:10,000 --> 00:45:17,000
And I went to wave to the people and it changed like from joy. Everybody was jippy-kaiyenne. When I first went out there, that's why I went to wave.

352
00:45:17,000 --> 00:45:21,000
Because I don't know me at the minute. And nobody out here but me. There must be a plot for me.

353
00:45:21,000 --> 00:45:29,000
And when I went the wave, it's like somebody snapped their finger and all the joy and happiness turned into anangren, venom, and hatred.

354
00:45:29,000 --> 00:45:33,000
And that's exactly what happened 15 years on that victory stand in Mexico City.

355
00:45:33,000 --> 00:45:41,000
Now, why did God show it to me? I'm humble that he reached out into the beaches of the world and picked up a grain of sand and threw it on the table with my name.

356
00:45:41,000 --> 00:45:49,000
And they said, you have to do this. I didn't tell them guys that I was trying to wake up to about the boycott you have to do this.

357
00:45:49,000 --> 00:45:58,000
All I say, man, let's put the cards on the table, man, and you make it a vested evaluation as to what this is all about and you make a decision.

358
00:45:58,000 --> 00:46:03,000
And they said, you should say we're going to the games. I didn't have the right to tell them you can't go to the games.

359
00:46:03,000 --> 00:46:08,000
You're training all your life. If you feel like it's one point for you to go, go.

360
00:46:08,000 --> 00:46:14,000
But in retrospect, now they sit back and they would just say, now who was right?

361
00:46:14,000 --> 00:46:24,000
Because all the time that I was going through trials and tribulations or Tommy Smith was going through trials and tribulations or peed and no more was going through trials and tribulations, there was jippy-kaiyenne.

362
00:46:24,000 --> 00:46:29,000
We made the wrong move. They made a bad move. They should have never did what they did.

363
00:46:29,000 --> 00:46:43,000
Now we didn't dwell in the storm. Now here are kids. Come back and talk to my, oh man, I think those statues that they built the San Jose State, I should have a brick dining with my name on it.

364
00:46:43,000 --> 00:46:53,000
Why should you have a brick with you on that? Well, we all ran together. If that statue had me breaking the tape passing the baton,

365
00:46:53,000 --> 00:47:00,000
I would be glad to have a brick with your name on it. I said, but that statue depicts something greater than athletics.

366
00:47:00,000 --> 00:47:06,000
You could have been a part of it. I don't understand. See, and then I said, well, let's take this hypothetical trip again.

367
00:47:06,000 --> 00:47:15,000
You want to roll me? Let's have some discussion about this. And this is for anybody out there in the audience right now. This is something for you to wait.

368
00:47:15,000 --> 00:47:23,000
Some of the approaches you will tell you say you can make a difference in society. You have to sacrifice in order to make this difference.

369
00:47:23,000 --> 00:47:34,000
You didn't want to do anything and you thought that you made the right decision. And here we are 40 years later things turn around and you think that, hey, I should jump on the bandwagon because I was in that era, would you?

370
00:47:34,000 --> 00:47:49,000
Well, let's go on this train. What are we getting on a train for? We getting on this train to have some dialogue. Make you understand why I think a boycott is necessary to make me understand why you feel necessary for you to go to these games.

371
00:47:49,000 --> 00:47:59,000
So we have a consensus that we're going to talk about this. Yeah, let's get on the train. Let's roll. Now we getting on this train. And it's just like soldiers going to the first wall wall.

372
00:47:59,000 --> 00:48:08,000
Everybody outside with a American flag and they singing God bless America and they got their hearts and their heart tears in the eyes.

373
00:48:08,000 --> 00:48:15,000
And we're on the train having this discussion, but as a train rolling all down the line, they waving the flag and singing the song.

374
00:48:15,000 --> 00:48:24,000
And then somebody says, you know, man, I have a better understanding now why is it necessary for me to make a statement.

375
00:48:24,000 --> 00:48:34,000
I'm not saying that I'm a boycott. All I'm saying to you is that I understand. Oh, you understand? You mean we have a consensus that we understand why it's necessary.

376
00:48:34,000 --> 00:48:41,000
Now I'm reaching for the red lever. You know what the red lever is in the train. I'm stopping the train. What are you pulling the train? The lever fall.

377
00:48:41,000 --> 00:48:48,000
Okay, we're back. Okay.

378
00:48:48,000 --> 00:49:03,000
Yeah. Yeah. So what are we pulling the lever for? We're pulling the lever man to stop the train because if we ever get consensus, the consensus don't mean not if it's just a consensus that we know about.

379
00:49:03,000 --> 00:49:12,000
We have to stop the train to put the banners on the side of the train to let the world know that we have a consensus about the pros and cons of this boycott.

380
00:49:12,000 --> 00:49:24,000
That potentially we might pull it together to do this. Now as a train begins to roll after we get the banners on, all of those people that's out there singing God bless America, they no longer did.

381
00:49:24,000 --> 00:49:31,000
Because they don't like the fact that we talking about we going boycott the limited. They don't like the fact that we talk about we're not going to represent America.

382
00:49:31,000 --> 00:49:37,000
That's like the soldier say I'm not going to war for you. We don't like the fact that you say you're not going to war.

383
00:49:37,000 --> 00:49:45,000
So okay, we rolling. Now in the place of those people that was out there, they're no longer there, but you know what took their place?

384
00:49:45,000 --> 00:49:54,000
Bombs and missiles and fire bombs coming to the train that the trains on fire smoke may have.

385
00:49:54,000 --> 00:50:02,000
And now here 45 years later you come back and tell me you deserve a brick. Well if you deserve a brick step on up here, I need you to do something for me.

386
00:50:02,000 --> 00:50:08,000
What's that John? Open up your shirt. Pull up your pants like roll up your sleeve. What are you looking for?

387
00:50:08,000 --> 00:50:19,000
Well, man, I'm looking for burns. If you don't have burns on your body, such as Mr. Smith or such as Mr. Norman or such as John Colors, then that means when things got hot, you bailed.

388
00:50:19,000 --> 00:50:30,000
And that's exactly what happened. And you know what came to my mind from that point is that individuals get locked up in the fact that I'm afraid to offend my oppressor.

389
00:50:30,000 --> 00:50:42,000
Those individuals that got their foot on their neck are holding up from getting fed education or fair housing or fair health care. They're the oppressors, but I know you wrong, but I'm afraid to offend you because you might get mad.

390
00:50:42,000 --> 00:50:51,000
Well, shit, John Colors don't care about what you get mad because I'm a die one day anyway. I might as well die standing on my feet and swallowed in the mud.

391
00:50:51,000 --> 00:51:04,000
And they have to understand that I'm a loving guy, but yet and still I was raised to be responsible and I'm being responsible to no one else to my kids and to the kids.

392
00:51:04,000 --> 00:51:15,000
Let me ask you to talk about influences. You talked a little bit about your family, maybe a little bit more about your parents, but also, you know, we're talking about your days and track and high school and all.

393
00:51:15,000 --> 00:51:24,000
And I know you got to listen to and get to know a little bit, Mr. Malcolm X. If you could talk about. Yes, that him. Well, let's go a little bit deeper than Malcolm X.

394
00:51:24,000 --> 00:51:35,000
Okay. When I was a kid, I was looking for religion. Why was I looking for religion because there was a lot of voice in my life. You know, a lot of things I'm thinking about did just didn't have answers.

395
00:51:35,000 --> 00:51:50,000
So I'm seeking out answers. So I found God. I found religion and I found a church called Abyssinia Baptist Church. And I told my mother and father my brother about it and we decided that we was going to go to Abyssinia Baptist Church.

396
00:51:50,000 --> 00:52:00,000
We get to the church and we see Adam Clayton Powell senior Adam Clayton Powell senior look like my father.

397
00:52:00,000 --> 00:52:09,000
But then one day we went to church and Adam Clayton Powell senior was sick and he came out to the poor pit and he said, I'm not doing well.

398
00:52:09,000 --> 00:52:15,000
I have a fever. I'm not going to preach the sermon today. I'm going to let my son preach the sermon.

399
00:52:15,000 --> 00:52:25,000
And I'm asking my father to say, who is this son daddy? And I see this white fella over there putting on the road. My father pointed there he is there.

400
00:52:25,000 --> 00:52:34,000
And I say, where? He said, God putting the road one. I said, daddy, that's not his son. That's a white man. He said, no son, that's his son.

401
00:52:34,000 --> 00:52:48,000
That's Adam Clayton Powell junior. And when he got up there and preached and wasn't about the color of his skin, it was about the content of his heart and his spirit and his mind based on what he was preaching.

402
00:52:48,000 --> 00:52:55,000
And then the thing that he said, after which was probably more profound than me is to tell the people to keep the faith.

403
00:52:55,000 --> 00:53:02,000
That's something that was like every day because he felt the pain and he knew the hell that people was going through.

404
00:53:02,000 --> 00:53:14,000
People of color, not just handing that things, but around the world. And at the same time, I remember my father telling me years ago, he's not passing.

405
00:53:14,000 --> 00:53:28,000
And I'm going to look like passing what daddy's and he said, he's not passing to be a white man. And I remember looking at my father and I said, daddy, you tell me that people ashamed of who they are that they would try and be somebody else.

406
00:53:28,000 --> 00:53:37,000
And he said to me, he said, no son, he said, they're not ashamed, although some of them might be a little overzealous. I know it overzealous man.

407
00:53:37,000 --> 00:53:49,000
So he says to me, he says son, he says, not today don't want to be black. On the other side of the street, he said, well white folks live, that standard life is better.

408
00:53:49,000 --> 00:54:00,000
If they can go and have a better standard life, then they cross over if their skin is fear skinned, that they can pass as being a white man to have a better standard life.

409
00:54:00,000 --> 00:54:12,000
And you know what I equated that to? It's not that people want to leave Cuba and risk their lives coming across the water, leave Haiti, risk their lives coming across the water and force the projection.

410
00:54:12,000 --> 00:54:18,000
If Cuba is bad or Haiti is bad, they leave in their country because they think they country or they present it as bad.

411
00:54:18,000 --> 00:54:26,000
They leave in their country and risking their lives for the same reason those white, young, light, skinned, skinned individuals cross the line.

412
00:54:26,000 --> 00:54:35,000
It's because they want a better standard life. And any man, irregard, so what your ethnic background is, she want to have a better standard life for their families.

413
00:54:35,000 --> 00:54:46,000
So I learned these things very early. So I got a whole, I haven't taken Paul and I put him in my system.

414
00:54:46,000 --> 00:54:55,000
There was another guy, Marcus Govy. I began to study Marcus Govy because they used to have Marcus Govy parade up and down New York and Harlem.

415
00:54:55,000 --> 00:55:02,000
And my brother used to be one of the tumble that's flipping the stick in the air in the whole nine yards and I used to look at him.

416
00:55:02,000 --> 00:55:09,000
But then I began to look away from him and began to look at the symbols that they had behind him and the parade.

417
00:55:09,000 --> 00:55:21,000
And then I'm going to start, who is this guy Marcus Govy? And what is Marcus Govy noted for? Marcus Govy got ships and he told black people in America say, hey man, I got these ships.

418
00:55:21,000 --> 00:55:33,000
Get on the ships. Let's go back to Africa so you can meet up with yourself. You can find out who you are. And retrospect when we look at that today, that's the biggest flaw that black people have.

419
00:55:33,000 --> 00:55:48,000
We still in 2013 don't know who the hell we are as eraser people. So that's one of our biggest problems now with the drug scene with the, the 15th and wrap music and this respect for seniors.

420
00:55:48,000 --> 00:55:59,000
And a whole nine yards based on the fact that we've been hidden from ourselves. So okay, so I study Marcus. Paul Roberson.

421
00:55:59,000 --> 00:56:09,000
I study Paul Roberson. And that's one of my greatest heroes because this man sacrificed everything for the mayor fact that he had everything.

422
00:56:09,000 --> 00:56:26,000
He's a Burr-Tone singer. He's a Rhodes scholar. He's an entertainer. He's a movie star. He had everything going for him. All he had to do was zip his lip. But it wasn't about him.

423
00:56:26,000 --> 00:56:38,000
He said, man, it's about my past. It's about my neighborhood. It's about my community. It's about those that doesn't have what I had that can't speak for themselves. So the same thing that I did, he did.

424
00:56:38,000 --> 00:56:53,000
He used to tell us that he had as a springboard for him to be a voice for people. They call him a communist. They call me a communist in 1968. The same reason. And you know why they call me a communist? Because I had the left arm opposed to the right arm.

425
00:56:53,000 --> 00:57:07,000
But it didn't stop me to determine from what the truth is and where I need to go. It didn't stop him. I mean, they took his past forward away from him. They did the tremendous amount of things to him. But it didn't break his spirit in terms of where he was going.

426
00:57:07,000 --> 00:57:18,000
Then I hear as a young individual on the radio one more time. This guy speaking on the radio. And I'm saying, wow, this is profound. Who is this guy?

427
00:57:18,000 --> 00:57:36,000
Well, they say his name is Mark. Oh, man, I love what he said because I heard nobody outside my father speak the way he's speaking. Now here's somebody. My father didn't have no corner where he can go get on the box that speaks to the community. But he did speak truth in the house.

428
00:57:36,000 --> 00:57:42,000
Now, here's a guy on the radio speaking for the world of here. Who is he?

429
00:57:42,000 --> 00:57:51,000
Marka Max. Name Marka Max. I didn't know about the Muslim set. His name is X.

430
00:57:51,000 --> 00:58:02,000
Then he said he was coming to head the mosque on a hundred and sixteen street. Now, hundred sixteen street at that time was a drug and festive. That's probably why they put the mosque there to try and clean up some of that.

431
00:58:02,000 --> 00:58:09,000
And when he went down there, I remember telling my father, say, daddy, I'm going down a hundred sixteen street to hear Marka Max.

432
00:58:09,000 --> 00:58:16,000
My father said, some of you go down there. Don't you get in no trouble. Now, daddy, I ain't looking for no trouble. I'm going to hear him.

433
00:58:16,000 --> 00:58:30,000
Now, I remember going down there and sitting in the front row the first time and listening to him and all. When I went in there, the first thing that blew me away is because when I went in there, just like I was looking for Adam Clayton Powell, who is Marka Max? Which one is Marka Max?

434
00:58:30,000 --> 00:58:40,000
Over there. Marka Max was a fair skin dude, light skin. And I'm looking at him and said, man, I can't be Marka Max. This guy is blowing too black to for him to be Marka Max.

435
00:58:40,000 --> 00:58:49,000
Showed enough when he started talking my lip fell open. It was him. And I'm sitting this close to him and listening to him.

436
00:58:49,000 --> 00:59:01,000
And I can just feel the blood just running through my body, man. I couldn't sit still. I was just with excitement for me to be there and see somebody live that I could touch that was talking like that.

437
00:59:01,000 --> 00:59:14,000
Because the way he was talking is the way I was feeling because I'm seeing what's happening in my community. And at the same time, when you see these things, man, it's the difference when you see them and your peers don't see them. They're still in the basketball.

438
00:59:14,000 --> 00:59:22,000
When we were younger, they're still in the spin in the bottle. They're still in the playing post office with the girls. And I'm looking at it. It's something deeper than that.

439
00:59:22,000 --> 00:59:29,000
I don't have time to spin the bottle and play the post office and jump in Jackson and loadies and all. I'm trying to get to the meat of things.

440
00:59:29,000 --> 00:59:41,000
Yeah, he is talking the exact same way I was feeling. So then I started to go back. I think the second and third time I went there and asked him, I waited around and I said, tell him I said, Miss Dex, is that possible?

441
00:59:41,000 --> 00:59:55,000
I can go with you from this location to your next location. And he looked at me and he smiled. I never forget he had a big dimple in his chin. And he says to me, he says, why do you want to go with me?

442
00:59:55,000 --> 01:00:05,000
And say, because I want to learn, I want to ask you questions. And he liked my answer. And he said, yes, she didn't come with me. He said, if you can keep up.

443
01:00:05,000 --> 01:00:16,000
I didn't know what he meant. Keep up. And so it dawned on me when I was walking with him was like walking my two older brothers because they were tall and with fast walking.

444
01:00:16,000 --> 01:00:31,000
I used to have to jog to keep up with them. But with my command, the jog to keep up with him, just the same. But I was learning a lot from him. And I had built the bond with him. And when Dr. When my my comments got killed at the auto bomb bar room.

445
01:00:31,000 --> 01:00:45,000
I was supposed to be there that Sunday. And we decided, me and some of the guys that was with machine metal trades on the track team that I was going to go try and get my driver's license that Monday.

446
01:00:45,000 --> 01:00:59,000
And we took a road trip and drove up the Buffalo New York, not Buffalo, but a beer mountain. And we passed by West Point. And just as we passed by West Point, it came on the news that Malcolm X was shot.

447
01:00:59,000 --> 01:01:14,000
Man, we turned around. We shot back to the hospital. By the time we got back to the hospital, he was gone. And everybody was milling around. And I could tell you, man, probably better part of 40 years, that 40 years, but 20 years of my life.

448
01:01:14,000 --> 01:01:22,000
I felt real bad. It felt like if I was in the auto bomb bar room that day, I could have did something to prevent him from dying.

449
01:01:22,000 --> 01:01:30,000
It took 20 years for me to die just that Malcolm X was born to this world to die that day.

450
01:01:30,000 --> 01:01:42,000
I was born into this world to be on that victory stand in Mexico. Certain individuals are born to be here to do certain things like that young kid, trade bond mod.

451
01:01:42,000 --> 01:01:58,000
He was born to die that day to try and wake society up. And just to be in that fold, man, just to be there, you humbled when you really figured out you began to look and say, you know, like Martin wanted to live too.

452
01:01:58,000 --> 01:02:10,000
When I was sad to meet with Martin Luther King, and after me was over in the meeting the consensus of the meeting was he wanted to be supportive of the Olympic boycott.

453
01:02:10,000 --> 01:02:18,000
You know, and that's a heavy thing. You know, you involved in the civil rights movement. You know, you know, after you get involved in the boycott.

454
01:02:18,000 --> 01:02:30,000
And after the meeting I asked him, I said to him, I said, I said, Mr. King, if you ever play any sports, then he gave me a little smart remark like I can't play pool.

455
01:02:30,000 --> 01:02:39,000
And I remember when he came out of that room in the hotel, I remember sitting there and I'm looking at luminaries that was dead that we seen on TV.

456
01:02:39,000 --> 01:02:44,000
But I still didn't put the dots together, think that I'm going to be in the presence of Dr. Martin Luther King.

457
01:02:44,000 --> 01:02:51,000
My household, Dr. King was like God's first lieutenant that he sent in. That's the way we was raised, believed it's.

458
01:02:51,000 --> 01:03:02,000
And man, I'm sitting there. And when that door opened and Dr. King walked out, like I was like living like wow.

459
01:03:02,000 --> 01:03:09,000
And he could see that I was like out of my element, probably me and some other people that was there too.

460
01:03:09,000 --> 01:03:16,000
If Dr. King wanted to be a deaf, jam, kind, comedian, he could have been that because he cracked some jokes.

461
01:03:16,000 --> 01:03:21,000
He saw and he cracked jokes, man, he loosened everybody up. Then we got an immediate conversation.

462
01:03:21,000 --> 01:03:26,000
He said that he didn't want to be the number one figure for the Olympic boycott.

463
01:03:26,000 --> 01:03:30,000
He wanted Harry Edwards to do that, but he wanted to be second in command.

464
01:03:30,000 --> 01:03:34,000
And when he come back from Memphis, he's going to go full blown.

465
01:03:34,000 --> 01:03:37,000
Can we just back a minute and say what that meeting was?

466
01:03:37,000 --> 01:03:39,000
The meeting was...

467
01:03:39,000 --> 01:03:40,000
And who Harry Edwards?

468
01:03:40,000 --> 01:03:46,000
The Harry Edwards, Professor Harry Edwards was the organiser he had ever felt about a name of Ken Knows.

469
01:03:46,000 --> 01:03:54,000
They were the organiser for the potential Olympic boycott of the 1960 Olympics.

470
01:03:54,000 --> 01:04:02,000
Tommy Smith had made a statement in Japan about a possible boycott.

471
01:04:02,000 --> 01:04:05,000
And I think that came off the top of his head.

472
01:04:05,000 --> 01:04:09,000
It kind of snowballed to the point where people started talking about it.

473
01:04:09,000 --> 01:04:17,000
And I think it clicked and resonated with Dr. Edwards, Professor Edwards and Professor Knows.

474
01:04:17,000 --> 01:04:19,000
And then they started putting together the organiser.

475
01:04:19,000 --> 01:04:22,000
And when they did this, I was off the scene.

476
01:04:22,000 --> 01:04:23,000
I wasn't on the scene.

477
01:04:23,000 --> 01:04:29,000
And I was going to school at East Texas State dealing with my own enclosed racism.

478
01:04:29,000 --> 01:04:38,000
And when they started becoming public, then I heard about what was happening in the sound of the thing with the potential boycott.

479
01:04:38,000 --> 01:04:43,000
So I'm stepping up speaking and fighting the racial issues there at East Texas State University.

480
01:04:43,000 --> 01:04:47,000
Let's just catch up chronologically and then we'll get to that meeting.

481
01:04:47,000 --> 01:04:48,000
Okay, you take a break.

482
01:04:48,000 --> 01:04:49,000
Yeah.

483
01:04:49,000 --> 01:04:50,000
And then we're back.

484
01:04:50,000 --> 01:04:51,000
Great.

485
01:04:51,000 --> 01:04:58,000
So could you just tell us a little bit how you ended up at East Texas and what you faced when you were there?

486
01:04:58,000 --> 01:05:06,000
As I stated earlier, I was married in my senior year in high school.

487
01:05:06,000 --> 01:05:12,000
We had petitioned to get an apartment in the city housing project.

488
01:05:12,000 --> 01:05:17,000
I was running track at the time and I was running a track meet in New Jersey.

489
01:05:17,000 --> 01:05:20,000
It was a guy named Pete Peterson, I think.

490
01:05:20,000 --> 01:05:28,000
He was a student at East Texas State University and he saw me run.

491
01:05:28,000 --> 01:05:32,000
And he said, man, you think about going to college?

492
01:05:32,000 --> 01:05:34,000
And I said, not really.

493
01:05:34,000 --> 01:05:37,000
And he said to me, he said, listen.

494
01:05:37,000 --> 01:05:39,000
He said, I think I can get you a scholarship.

495
01:05:40,000 --> 01:05:44,000
And he said, I'm going to give you a name and number two is Coach.

496
01:05:44,000 --> 01:05:49,000
And I guess he saw some talent probably more than I took for granted.

497
01:05:49,000 --> 01:05:51,000
I'm just doing my thing.

498
01:05:51,000 --> 01:05:57,000
And the coach called me and said, listen, he said, you know, I liked off of you a scholarship.

499
01:05:57,000 --> 01:06:00,000
And you know, you can come down.

500
01:06:00,000 --> 01:06:01,000
It's nice.

501
01:06:01,000 --> 01:06:02,000
It's nice down here.

502
01:06:02,000 --> 01:06:04,000
It's no prejudice or anything.

503
01:06:04,000 --> 01:06:10,000
You know, when you go the way to the track meet all the wives and the kids going to bus to the track meet,

504
01:06:10,000 --> 01:06:13,000
you get a chance for ride horses the whole nine yards.

505
01:06:13,000 --> 01:06:16,000
Something to myself, I said, wow, that might be nice.

506
01:06:16,000 --> 01:06:20,000
You know, you get a chance to get my daughter because I own this daughter was born.

507
01:06:20,000 --> 01:06:25,000
And I said, it might be nice to get my daughter a chance to grow up outside of the city.

508
01:06:25,000 --> 01:06:27,000
It might be a nice situation.

509
01:06:27,000 --> 01:06:29,000
So I said, okay.

510
01:06:29,000 --> 01:06:35,000
And at the same time, I was supposed to leave to go to East Texas State.

511
01:06:35,000 --> 01:06:41,000
I got a notification from New York City Hall and authority that we was accepted to get an apartment in the project.

512
01:06:41,000 --> 01:06:47,000
You know, you think, I'm thinking economics, then I'm saying, if I got an apartment, my rent will be as a sealant to my rent.

513
01:06:47,000 --> 01:06:50,000
And you know, I'll be able to sustain myself.

514
01:06:50,000 --> 01:06:52,000
Then the scholarship came.

515
01:06:52,000 --> 01:06:57,000
So the decision I had to make, you know, as to what I was going to go to East Texas State,

516
01:06:57,000 --> 01:07:03,000
or what I was going to just stay and work in New York and be satisfied with the guy that gave me the terms of having that apartment in the project.

517
01:07:03,000 --> 01:07:06,000
But you wouldn't be running if you took that.

518
01:07:06,000 --> 01:07:09,000
Oh, well, I can run for the clubs and so forth.

519
01:07:09,000 --> 01:07:18,000
So I had some dialogue with my wife and I was telling her, well, you know, it might be nice, you know, for a baby to get a chance to grow up outside of the city.

520
01:07:18,000 --> 01:07:26,000
And I was telling her, I said, well, if we're going to go, I'll go down and I'll check the turf, I'll sort of speak.

521
01:07:26,000 --> 01:07:34,000
And my wife told me she said, no, if you go, we go, we're a family.

522
01:07:34,000 --> 01:07:39,000
So I ain't going to argue with that. It's the fact. So I said, okay, we'll go.

523
01:07:39,000 --> 01:07:44,000
And it was a fellow by the name of Dennis Dice, he was Jamaican.

524
01:07:44,000 --> 01:07:49,000
American Jamaican. I guess he was born Jamaican. Left when he was young.

525
01:07:49,000 --> 01:07:54,000
Okay. Dennis Dice.

526
01:07:54,000 --> 01:07:56,000
Okay. So yes.

527
01:07:56,000 --> 01:07:58,000
Hold on.

528
01:07:58,000 --> 01:08:03,000
We're still rolling.

529
01:08:03,000 --> 01:08:05,000
Okay. Dennis Dice.

530
01:08:05,000 --> 01:08:13,000
Yes. So Dennis Dice was a young guy. You know, we grew up together, but we didn't grow up together, but we used to run track in New York together.

531
01:08:13,000 --> 01:08:17,000
And he was young, had his wife and young daughter as well.

532
01:08:17,000 --> 01:08:19,000
And we were going down there.

533
01:08:19,000 --> 01:08:25,000
And Dennis had a different agenda. Dennis was born, I think, in Jamaica.

534
01:08:25,000 --> 01:08:29,000
He used to make statements, but he wasn't black. He was Jamaican.

535
01:08:29,000 --> 01:08:34,000
And Dennis was getting confused. His ethnicity with his nationality.

536
01:08:34,000 --> 01:08:40,000
And I was trying to make him understand. He was a darker skin, black person.

537
01:08:40,000 --> 01:08:44,000
And I was trying to make him understand. I mean, he said, you're not black. You're Jamaican.

538
01:08:44,000 --> 01:08:52,000
And the bottom line is, if the police was a kick down the door right now, he's going to probably whip you up more than me, just based on the texture of your skin.

539
01:08:52,000 --> 01:08:54,000
So don't say that you're not black. You are black.

540
01:08:54,000 --> 01:09:01,000
So when we got down to Texas, you know, we was buddy buddy. We were going to have each other's back when we got down there and the great divide came.

541
01:09:01,000 --> 01:09:06,000
You know, he looked at the coaches and said, let me slide up under the coach and be the coaches.

542
01:09:06,000 --> 01:09:13,000
I don't want to say boy, but I don't know other ways to say it. You know, that's what it was.

543
01:09:13,000 --> 01:09:23,000
And I saw that right away. But even greater than that, when I landed in Dallas, Fort Worth, and there was nowhere near the monstrosity airport that they had today.

544
01:09:23,000 --> 01:09:31,000
There was a little box, you know, like box calls almost. And I remember seeing the bronze statue, the Texas Ranger bronze statue in there.

545
01:09:31,000 --> 01:09:41,000
I had somewhere in the New Airport, you still see it. But when I looked at right at the statue, I saw a sign say, white's only.

546
01:09:41,000 --> 01:09:49,000
It was the restroom. And then I saw another sign say colors.

547
01:09:49,000 --> 01:09:57,000
It didn't say colors only, just colors. And anybody else wanted to go in there. But then I began to notice that the white restroom was pristine.

548
01:09:57,000 --> 01:10:01,000
Man, it was clean. You know, like you could cook eggs on the floor. It was so clean.

549
01:10:01,000 --> 01:10:07,000
And then the colored restroom, man, it had water running, toilet paper on the floor, and gnats and flies.

550
01:10:07,000 --> 01:10:15,000
I'm looking then, I'm looking at the water fountain airport. You couldn't go there. It was white's only. And didn't have no black water fountain.

551
01:10:15,000 --> 01:10:25,000
And then the other just whites only, like whatever you need some water. And then when the coach came, my name changed from John Coloss to boy.

552
01:10:25,000 --> 01:10:32,000
And I was really offended then because I was a young man at the time. But what offended me is because I had my daughter with me.

553
01:10:32,000 --> 01:10:39,000
And my wife with me, and he called me boy, and I'm telling them I said coach, my name is John Coloss. My name is boy.

554
01:10:39,000 --> 01:10:47,000
And then he went so far to use this word nigg-ruh. And he said it fast. And I thought he was saying nigg-ruh.

555
01:10:47,000 --> 01:10:55,000
And I remember that he is raising up on my neck. And I looked at him, I said, what you saying? What you call me? And my wife was kind of like pulling my arm.

556
01:10:55,000 --> 01:11:02,000
No, baby, he didn't say that. He said something else. And I remember telling him, I said, well, he said he damn close. He better be careful.

557
01:11:02,000 --> 01:11:13,000
And from that point on, I knew I was going to have problems. And I was always the type of individuals to take my parents into account in terms of their economic base.

558
01:11:13,000 --> 01:11:22,000
They didn't have the money for me to pick up the phone. I'm sure if I'd have called and said, daddy, I made a mistake. I needed to get out of here. They would do what they had to do to get me back to it.

559
01:11:22,000 --> 01:11:31,000
But I wouldn't do it. I said, well, we don't tough it out. And when I got in town, I realized that the school had just become integrated possibly a year, maybe two years before I got there.

560
01:11:31,000 --> 01:11:42,000
So, you know, like as I stated earlier, you know, we've been supposed to be emancipated for 150 years. And we still just above being a slave. You know, in a lot of instances.

561
01:11:42,000 --> 01:11:51,000
And down there, it was pretty much that same way. Although they said we were fully integrated school, they still had the old slave master attitude.

562
01:11:51,000 --> 01:12:01,000
I remember when my daughter was outside playing one time and with little white kid. And you know, kids don't know them. But no race. They just kids having fun.

563
01:12:01,000 --> 01:12:18,000
And the father must have looked out the window and saw his daughter playing my daughter. And he went and he screamed in his daughter and screamed in my daughter and used the N word again and telling the daughter, I don't know once you playing with this little.

564
01:12:18,000 --> 01:12:28,000
Now, my daughter didn't know what it said, but what it meant no more than I knew what it meant. I had an experience like that one time my great uncle in New York. She didn't know what that word meant.

565
01:12:28,000 --> 01:12:41,000
It was just a tone and the way the man confronted her. It scared it. It came to the house crying. And I asked her what happened. And she said, man, start hollering and screaming and telling her daughter don't play with her.

566
01:12:41,000 --> 01:12:58,000
And I went outside and tried to get out of line with me. And I remember getting in this guy's face and in the back of my brain, I'm saying, I'm going to have to leave here because if I kill this man, everything that I stand for is going to go out the window.

567
01:12:58,000 --> 01:13:14,000
But I can't stay here and allow them to do what they're doing. And the school was, I say, had racial problems from the president all the way down just above the jenus in the school, all the the maintenance people were black.

568
01:13:14,000 --> 01:13:24,000
But they had the vibe that was so deep. And then at the same time, they didn't never experience individuals such as myself coming down there.

569
01:13:24,000 --> 01:13:43,000
Like I said, I was my own man. They could dictate to me. I remember the coach telling me, say, John, whatever you do, don't talk to none of the white girls down here. And I remember telling them, I said, well, tell me, you tell me don't talk to the white girl. Well, what if the white girl come to talk to me? What do I do then? You tell me don't talk to him.

570
01:13:43,000 --> 01:14:01,000
You know, I remember going to the Texas first indoor meet at like a cow palace, Dan Dallas. And I remember the browns, why they got, you know, sarcastic to me and start talking all kind of off the wall nonsense.

571
01:14:01,000 --> 01:14:12,000
And I had to set up straight and tell her, say, you know, something's brown. I said, let me just say something, you know, the stakes that you have when you're playing tonight, you get them stakes and you're played as a result of what I'm doing.

572
01:14:12,000 --> 01:14:27,000
So I said, let's not get this confused as to what my role is and what your role is. You used to tell them other kids that don't come tell me nothing like that. So right away, sharp eyes rolled back in their heads because she wasn't ready for the response that I gave her.

573
01:14:27,000 --> 01:14:40,000
I was, no, it was dumb or brown. I had a situation where I'm running, I'm running everything doing the course of my time. They all attract me some winning and everything.

574
01:14:40,000 --> 01:14:51,000
And I remember the, now Bobby, Bobby moral is a great sprinter, one in 1956, Olympics, 100 and 200. And he's out of the Abilene Christian.

575
01:14:51,000 --> 01:15:06,000
And I might say a class guy, class act, much respectful Bobby moral. But don't my brown made a statement after I run and attract me. And he said, John Coloss is as great as Bobby moral.

576
01:15:06,000 --> 01:15:19,000
And I guess Bobby at the time was, you know, like God's gift to Texas. And a lot of the people was offended that he said that a black man could be as great as Bobby moral.

577
01:15:19,000 --> 01:15:34,000
And the next day he got a retracting statement. Yeah, you know, I looked at that and I said, oh, well, I see where he coming from. But towards the end of our relationship, we were getting ready to go to the, to the Lone Star conference.

578
01:15:34,000 --> 01:15:46,000
As a fellow that I, I can say, I'll be friend of him. He'd be friend of me and made me comfortable with. I never fell about a name, but Terry Barnett White fellow.

579
01:15:46,000 --> 01:15:59,000
I could go so far as to say Terry Barnett, I put Terry Barnett in the class of John Brown and Peter Norman. You know, he's a white guy that was on his own plane and had love for humanity.

580
01:15:59,000 --> 01:16:09,000
And he came to me and he told me, he said, John, you see, I know things that's rough here, man. He said, but if you and I stay together, man, we can make a difference here.

581
01:16:09,000 --> 01:16:24,000
And I liked what he said. And we became buddies. And we stayed there. And I remember when we was getting ready to go to the conference, like I said, I'd run everything, you know, just like Jesse Ones and Berlin, you know, run everything and you tied.

582
01:16:24,000 --> 01:16:35,000
And we get ready to go to the conference meeting. And I walk in the locker room. And this is the day before we spoke to get in, and we didn't go in buses. We went in station wagons.

583
01:16:35,000 --> 01:16:45,000
So he's got on the wall. He wants me to run a 350, then he want me to run a 280, then he want me to run on 150. And you know, for time.

584
01:16:45,000 --> 01:16:58,000
So I'm looking at him. See, man, I'm not running. This is man. It's crazy. It's my boy. See, man, no, make no promise. Man, he's out. It's my I'm not running this. If he don't know that I'm capable of doing it now, why am I going to run this approach? I'm not doing it.

585
01:16:58,000 --> 01:17:12,000
So we get out there. He got this stop. He's now come on, son. Come on. You know, you my house. I want you to run so and so. So when we started off for the 380. I'm on the turn and I took off running.

586
01:17:12,000 --> 01:17:22,000
And I must have run maybe 60 yards and I stopped running and I walked and it was building a platform for the graduating class that he out in the stadium.

587
01:17:22,000 --> 01:17:33,000
And I walk all the way around the track and I'm walking down and he walks down and he picks up a hammer. And he started walking towards me and tell me, nigga, I'm tired of you.

588
01:17:33,000 --> 01:17:41,000
And I looked at him and I told him, I said, dummy, let me tell you something. I said, you better hope that that hammer is liquid because you come to me without making you eat it.

589
01:17:41,000 --> 01:17:47,000
And I remember his son, Danny was on the wall and I said, Danny, I said, why don't you come down and take this ass working for your father.

590
01:17:47,000 --> 01:17:52,000
And the son said, I'm not in that. I'm not involved in that.

591
01:17:52,000 --> 01:18:00,000
But then I remember stripping down took my shorts, my job, everything I've right there in the field. The guys like they're playing football.

592
01:18:00,000 --> 01:18:08,000
And at that time, if a black man dropped the football, they'd call them all kind of stupid this and stupid dad and the whole nine yards.

593
01:18:08,000 --> 01:18:14,000
And a lot of them was caught in the quandary where I couldn't figure out why they was accepting this. I figured out later.

594
01:18:14,000 --> 01:18:22,000
And that was because if they're in the left school that had been drafted before they could get into another school and they had been writing Vietnam.

595
01:18:22,000 --> 01:18:28,000
And it took me a while to figure that one out. Why wouldn't you step up and say certain things? You know, they wouldn't do it.

596
01:18:28,000 --> 01:18:33,000
So anyway, I took all my stuff and doing this face and I said, man, I'm done.

597
01:18:33,000 --> 01:18:42,000
And I went inside and ripped my name off the locker, took all my stuff, took it over by the day. And I'm in the shower and he comes up in the shower and that son.

598
01:18:42,000 --> 01:18:47,000
I might have been a little hasty and I'm looking at him and say, dumb, leave here.

599
01:18:47,000 --> 01:18:52,000
Leave here because I was so mad, man, you go about to die in here. Just leave.

600
01:18:53,000 --> 01:19:07,000
Now, I remember calling my wife and telling my wife, start packing, we leave it. My wife was working for this guy was the mayor of the town, but he was the chairman of the journalist department in the school too.

601
01:19:07,000 --> 01:19:17,000
Now, my wife got the job with him. But incidentally, I might have my wife gave up a job. She was executive secretary for one of the generals over on Ellis Island.

602
01:19:17,000 --> 01:19:29,000
So I don't think it was Ellis Island or another island over there. Anyway, she's general. So when we got down there, they promised all the job, you know, they can bust trips in the whole now.

603
01:19:29,000 --> 01:19:38,000
We got to get rid of that. So when I said, look, y'all don't have nothing for my wife, I'm gone. But she got the job with this guy.

604
01:19:38,000 --> 01:19:51,000
So I'm telling her, say, well, we leave it. So now I'm up in the student union, sitting out on the terrace and I'm telling all the guys, say, man, it's been a nice run. I love you guys. I said, but I'm getting ready to get out of here.

605
01:19:51,000 --> 01:20:06,000
And they told me, what do you mean you get ready to go? So they had like a walkway and we up sitting on the balcony area and was like the vigilante committee. All the coaches, they didn't got together and they come in to walk up. John, we like to talk to you.

606
01:20:06,000 --> 01:20:18,000
And I said, tell him, I said, yeah, well, okay, well, we like to take you lunch and head like a little cafeteria downstairs and that's doing you in the building. So I said, well, if you want to take me to feed me, all those guys together, you take all of us and feed all of us.

607
01:20:18,000 --> 01:20:32,000
So they took them down, particularly like a pudding, did it. And they took me to a separate table. And they tell me, so a giant, you know, a dumb brown might have been hasting what he did. And he didn't mean this and he didn't mean that. And I said, no, he meant it.

608
01:20:32,000 --> 01:20:41,000
I said, I meant what I said, too. And I'm getting up out of here and let you could do to tell me. And they left.

609
01:20:41,000 --> 01:20:49,000
But my friend Terry, a boy, that came to me and Terry said to me, he said, John, he said, man, I know how you feel and I saw the answer that.

610
01:20:49,000 --> 01:21:04,000
And he said, but man, you know, we made a commitment. We made a bond. And the bond was to win the long star championship. And he said, he said, he said, there's no way in the world that we would ever win this thing if you leave it.

611
01:21:04,000 --> 01:21:13,000
And he said, man, I just hope that you would stay with the commitment that we made you and I made. And I told Terry, I said, Terry, that's the best thing I heard all year.

612
01:21:13,000 --> 01:21:24,000
I said, yeah, you right. We're going to go and we're going to win the long star camp. We went, we won. Now when football team won, football team in that time was probably about 85 to 90 percent white.

613
01:21:24,000 --> 01:21:38,000
When they won, they gave them these big, big ass rings. When we won the conference in track and field, they give us a little shoe with a flake. It wasn't even a dime as a flake.

614
01:21:38,000 --> 01:21:49,000
And give it to them. I said, what's this? He said, well, listen, what you get for winning the conference. I said, no, man, I don't want that. I said, everybody on the track team deserve no less than what you get a football team.

615
01:21:49,000 --> 01:22:01,000
Wait, not going to give you that. Oh, you're going to give it to me. I said, I'm telling you to give it to you. I'm telling you to give it to you. I said, I earned it. And everybody on this team earned it. So we eventually went and they gave the ring up.

616
01:22:01,000 --> 01:22:20,000
And we still had the ring today. But it got so ridiculous down there, not just in commerce, but throughout Texas. I had a situation where I was in Austin, Texas, and I was with a reporter and the photographer, two white guys for the school.

617
01:22:20,000 --> 01:22:36,000
And went into a bar to buy beer was hot day. Went into a bar and I had to go to the restroom and I told the bar, I said, bye, keep get these guys what they want. And I have a beer. I'm going to buy from the other guy come out. They drink it.

618
01:22:36,000 --> 01:22:52,000
You know, beer for me. It was two Hispanic guys shooting pool. So I said, bye, keep with my beer. He just ignored me went on. So then I say, bye, keep a back for beer. He said, we don't serve niggas in here.

619
01:22:52,000 --> 01:23:11,000
And I said, I don't ask for niggas for beer. And when he said something smart again, I reached across the kind of I grabbed him and I drug him and started dragging him over the kind of and the two Hispanic guys was playing pool. They rolled up and had to push things like bats to tell me, let him go.

620
01:23:11,000 --> 01:23:32,000
And I'm backing out of there. But when I backed out of there, I wasn't concerned about the Hispanic guys. I wasn't concerned about the bot. And I was concerned about the two white guys that was with me. I said, man, I'm buying the food, the booze for you. And you going to drink and you ain't concerned about my business. You ain't heard y'all say boo.

621
01:23:32,000 --> 01:23:49,000
So now I'm starting to look at them. And then it dawned on me. It escalated my brain. It wasn't even about them no more. It was about the fact that I was running all over the country with East Texas.

622
01:23:49,000 --> 01:24:07,000
I'm not just representing East Texas State University. I'm representing the state of Texas. And here I'm in the state capital and I go to a bar and mainly because of the color of my skin, I have to be disrespected. And I can't be served.

623
01:24:07,000 --> 01:24:25,000
Or we go on a bus and we go somewhere and we stop to eat. And the coach told me, well, you black guy is staring at the bus and the white kids, we're going to eat. Tell us what y'all want. And I have to step up and tell the coach, no, man, that's not the way I see it. If y'all going to the restaurant, we damn sure going to the restaurant.

624
01:24:25,000 --> 01:24:36,000
So we don't go in the restaurant. You don't go in the restaurant. And he was like offended that I'm confronting them like this. But I'm looking at sitting on man, that's not. I don't know how it was yesterday, but this society is today.

625
01:24:36,000 --> 01:24:53,000
So with these things, man, I had to go and I decided I got to leave East Texas. And I think it was really came to the clucks when he came in with that hammer because when he came with the hammer, I'm reflecting on what happened in Austin, Texas about the fact that I'm in the state capital.

626
01:24:53,000 --> 01:25:01,000
And I'm representing the state of Texas and I can't even get a beer. So it all kind of mesh together this time for me to leave.

627
01:25:01,000 --> 01:25:15,000
I left. I went back to New York and I was hoping my mother paint a kitchen in the farm rang. It was Professor Edwards. And he called me and told me, said, John, he says, uh,

628
01:25:15,000 --> 01:25:27,000
some people having a very important meeting and they asked me to invite you. You think you can get away and ask my mother, say, mine, they got a meeting. They asked me where I come.

629
01:25:27,000 --> 01:25:33,000
You think I can go and she said, yes, son, I can take care of the painting if they invite you to me, you need to be there.

630
01:25:33,000 --> 01:25:43,000
And I remember going down to the Marricana Hotel, right across from the old garden. I went down there and I remember walking into the lobby. You know kids that grew up in New York, you know, all of

631
01:25:43,000 --> 01:25:56,000
the way. We had to major mega hotels. I remember going into the hotel sitting in the lobby and looking at the chandeliers, the big pictures and mirrors. And I'm saying, man, I can get this chandelier, take it to my house.

632
01:25:56,000 --> 01:26:06,000
Because my mother loved furniture. She was a perfection. My mother's a type of woman. She put plastic going to sofa. You can't sit on the fatigued. So same way.

633
01:26:06,000 --> 01:26:16,000
So I shook that off and then I went to the desk and I asked for SCLC. I didn't know where that CLC was at the time, but I asked for it. And they told me, oh, yeah, go up so and so.

634
01:26:16,000 --> 01:26:31,000
And I went up there and I knocked in the door. And I believe was Andrew Young that came in open the door. And I was in awe of Andrew Young because I envisioned Andrew Young as being like 6364.

635
01:26:31,000 --> 01:26:42,000
And when I saw his statue, I was like in shock. And I'm thinking to myself all that time, I said, God, the guy that was shooting this picture must have been landed in the back and just shooting everything up because he looked so tall.

636
01:26:42,000 --> 01:27:00,000
But he was called you. He was nice. He invited me in. She's like soda, juice, water, milk, sandwich, cookies, you know. And I'm sitting there. And I'm just, you know, looking at these people and just think that I'm watching these people as a kid on TV and him. I'm in a room with him.

637
01:27:00,000 --> 01:27:10,000
But like I said earlier, I never put the dots together. He even faffish in my mind that Dr. King was in that room or that he was going to come to that room.

638
01:27:10,000 --> 01:27:23,000
And I said like 20 minutes later, he opened up a back bedroom door and he walked out there, man. And I was 50 feet tall. First thing I thought is, man, my mother need to be a rock in my pocket of bug on my lapel. She needs to be here right now.

639
01:27:23,000 --> 01:27:32,000
And I remember when I got home and I told my mother what happened. My mother said to me, see what son I was there. I was dead through you. You know, it was just heavy.

640
01:27:32,000 --> 01:27:47,000
But I asked Dr. King about him. Did he play any sports? And he said, no, I can't shoot pool. And I asked him, I said to him, I said, with Dr. King, why would you, why would you get involved in the Olympic Project for Human Rights?

641
01:27:47,000 --> 01:27:59,000
And he said to me, he said, Don, he said, that's a good question. And he says to me, he says, he said, imagine you being in a lake and you take the roadboat and you roll out to the center of the lake.

642
01:27:59,000 --> 01:28:11,000
And then you bring the oars in, you sit there and you be still and everything is still in serene. He said, you reach down, you pick up a rock and you reach over and you drop that rock. What happens?

643
01:28:11,000 --> 01:28:24,000
And I said, it creates vibrations. He smiled. He said, yes, it creates waves. He said, well, that rock is that Olympic boycott. He said, now it will arouse anything in that lake.

644
01:28:24,000 --> 01:28:38,000
And anything on the shore of that lake to let you know that something is a miss. He said, that's the Olympic boycott. He said, and the greatest thing about it is that you will wake the world up in a very nonviolent way.

645
01:28:38,000 --> 01:28:50,000
That carried me over to Mexico in terms of that demonstration. I want to do something that would be so powerful that would reach the ends of the earth and yet still be nonviolent.

646
01:28:50,000 --> 01:29:07,000
Yeah, we didn't have no father overtones whatsoever. And the second thing I asked him, I said to him, I said, Dr. King, I said, you said if you come back from Memphis and you told us in your speech in the meeting that they threaten your life.

647
01:29:07,000 --> 01:29:14,000
They sent you a letter to tell you to add a bullet with your name when you went into the way long. And they threaten your life. Why would you go back to Memphis?

648
01:29:14,000 --> 01:29:28,000
And he looked at me and when he looked at me, I used to have shades on dark shades. I still wear dark shades a lot of times. But I took my glasses and put them on my nose so I could look dead into his eyes. I don't know glass from what I'm going to see his eyes.

649
01:29:28,000 --> 01:29:41,000
I'm looking for fear. When a man tells you that somebody told them they're going to kill him, you're supposed to see a little shaky dance. The rocket you brought to him and I ain't she number loving a man's eyes for society.

650
01:29:41,000 --> 01:29:56,000
